text:
On the subject of stocks... I dont know how much of that game will be true. I don't think this is a good time to start investing. Also, remember how you felt in papers please? Welcome to Arstotzka.

There's more money in the stock market currently than there should be:
Most Banks and Hedge funds are over leveraged to a minimal of 5 to 1, some as high as 20 to 1 or more. Which means, if they only had 100 billion in cash, and leverage it on 10 to 1 ratio, they took a loan and now have 1 trillion to put in stocks. Most large banks and hedge funds do that cause they are all greedy, and they are literally gambling, except the big boys are the house. You can check Archegos hedge fund's leverage when they collapse. The reason why people say the stock market is in a bubble is because of this, there's more money in the market than there should because of overleveraging.

Next we have corruption. If they break any rules, they get a slap on the wrist, it's a cost of business. They make 100 Million breaking a rule, they fine them like 100k (including insider trading). Basically the SEC takes a cut and makes it look like it's doing its job. Everyone that was in charge and works for the SEC used to work for the banks and hedge funds. The billionaires are connected, the banks and hedgefund and lobbyist, by extension, the government is connected and is the reason why they are allowed to do this for decades. 2008 crash and bailout, them.

So there's two main ways they are currently breaking the "fair free market".
Brokers will sell your information, your trades, your position so the big boys can use that for their interest, often it's against yours with their algorithms and fiber optic cable a few blocks away so they can cut you in line after seeing your order. Depending on where you live, they can also not actually purchase the stock you place your order for, just gives ya a representative that mimics the price, but say they did so it doesn't affect the price of the stock. This when combined with Naked (counterfeit) short selling will drop the price of the stock.
Short selling is when you borrow a stock now and promise to give it back later, say it's worth $10, you sell it for that much, and if the price drops to $6 before you have to give it back, you can buy it for $6 and give it back and keep the difference of $4. If it went up, you have to buy it back for more and lose money.

Naked shorts (counterfeit) short selling is when they sell a part of the company they do not own. If there's 70mill total shares, they can counterfeit 140 million shares if they wanted to; basically selling the entire company they do not own, twice. It's illegal but no one will enforce it.
They like to do this because if they can get the company delisted, they keep all the money they made short selling with out having to give back the shares they owe, and it's tax free. If they can't it can end up being a short squeeze. There's historical examples of all of this to verify it and it's easy to google, there's documentaries of 2008 crash and wallstreet as well.
